The Mathematics of the Transformation from Cartesian coordinates to Frenet Frame.

Imagine your car is at point $P(x, y)$, and the closest segment of the road centerline is defined by waypoint $A$ and the next waypoint $B$.


1. Find the Closest WaypointFirst, you calculate the Euclidean distance from your car $P$ to every single waypoint on the map. You find the index of the waypoint with the absolute minimum distance. Let's call this waypoint $A$.


2. Define the Vectors
We create two vectors:

The Road Vector ($\vec{AB}$): The line connecting waypoint $A$ to the next waypoint $B$. This represents the direction of the lane.

The Car Vector ($\vec{AP}$): The line connecting waypoint $A$ to your car $P$.


3. Calculate Lateral Distance ($d$)

To find how far you are drifting from the center line, we need the perpendicular distance from $P$ to the line $AB$. We also need to know if you are on the left (negative $d$) or right (positive $d$). We do this using the Cross Product.

$$d = \frac{\vec{AB} \times \vec{AP}}{|\vec{AB}|}$$

(Note: If the cross product is positive, you are on the left of the center line. If negative, you are on the right).


4. Calculate Longitudinal Distance ($s$)

The $s$ value is the total distance along the road from the very beginning of the map.
First, we project the Car Vector onto the Road Vector using the Dot Product to find how far past waypoint $A$ the car has driven:

$$Proj = \frac{\vec{AP} \cdot \vec{AB}}{|\vec{AB}|}$$

Then, we simply add that projection to the cumulative $s$ value of waypoint $A$:

$$s = s_{A} + Proj$$
